# Calculating stream temperature metrics
Stream temperature metrics modified from Heck, M.P., Schultz, L.D., Hockman-Wert, D., Dinger, E.C., and Dunham, J.B., 2018, Monitoring stream temperatures—A guide for non-specialists: U.S. Geological Survey Techniques and Methods, book 3, chap. A25, 76 p., *https://doi.org/10.3133/tm3A25*. 

```{r metric calculations on cleaned data}
# Daily summaries on cleaned data
daily_summary <- df_cleaned %>%
  group_by(site, date, year, doy, period) %>%
  summarise(
    d_max = if(any(!is.na(temperature))) max(temperature, na.rm = TRUE) else NA_real_,
    d_mean = mean(temperature, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = 'drop'
  ) %>%
  filter(is.finite(d_max))

# Comprehensive Annual Metrics (13 Indicators form Heck et al. 2018)
annual_metrics <- daily_summary %>%
  group_by(site, year, period) %>%
  arrange(date) %>%
  mutate(
    roll7_max = rollmean(d_max, 7, fill = NA, align = "right"),
    roll7_mean = rollmean(d_mean, 7, fill = NA, align = "right")
  ) %>%
  summarise(
    days_in_record = n(),
    # Magnitude
    Max_Temp = safe_max(d_max),
    MWMT = safe_max(roll7_max),
    MWAT = safe_max(roll7_mean),
    # Timing
    MWMT_DOY = if(!is.na(MWMT)) doy[which.max(roll7_max)] else NA_integer_,
    # Variability and range
    Mean_Range = max(d_mean) - min(d_mean),
    Max_Range = max(d_max) - min(d_max), 
    Mean_Var = var(d_mean),
    Max_Var = var(d_max),
    # Threshold Counts
    Days_16C = sum(d_max > 16),
    Days_18C = sum(d_max > 18), 
    Days_20C = sum(d_max > 20),
    # Duration (Consecutive Streak) counts
    Consec_16C = max_consec(d_max, 16),
    Consec_18C = max_consec(d_max, 18),
    Consec_20C = max_consec(d_max, 20),
    .groups = 'drop'
  )
```

# Generate summary table of stream temperature metrics
1. Thermal Magnitude and Timing Metrics.
Maximum Temp ($T_{max}$): The single warmest instantaneous temperature recorded during the summer index period.
MWMT (Max Weekly Max Temp): The highest 7-day rolling average of daily maximum temperatures. 
MWAT (Max Weekly Average Temp): The highest 7-day rolling average of daily mean temperatures. This identifies the "chronic" thermal floor that fish must endure even at night.
MWMT (Julian Day): The day of the year (1–366) when the MWMT occurred. A shift to an earlier Peak Day post-fire may indicate a loss of riparian canopy that previously buffered early-summer solar radiation.

2. Variability and Range Metrics
Mean/Max Range: The difference between the highest and lowest daily mean or maximum values. 
Mean/Max Variance: A statistical measure of how much temperatures fluctuate around the average. High variance post-fire often points to increased vulnerability to solar heating after the canopy is removed.

3. Threshold and Duration Metrics (Biological Stress).
Days > 16, 18, 20°C: The total count of days where the daily maximum exceeded these thresholds. For example, $18^{\circ}C$ is a standard regulatory threshold in many Western states for maintaining suitable salmonid habitat.
Consec. Days > 16, 18, 20°C: The longest continuous "streak" of days above a threshold.

```{r summary table}
# Calculate Averages by Site and Period (Excluding Fire Year)
table_long <- annual_metrics %>%
  filter(period != "Fire Year") %>% # Exclude 2020 disturbance year
  group_by(site, period) %>%
  summarise(across(c(Max_Temp:Consec_20C, MWMT_DOY), \(x) mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)), .groups = "drop") %>%
  # IMPORTANT: This step creates the 'Value' column required by pivot_wider
  pivot_longer(cols = -c(site, period), names_to = "Metric", values_to = "Value")

# Reshape for Side-by-Side Comparison
final_table_df <- table_long %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = period, values_from = Value) %>%
  mutate(
    `Change (Δ)` = `Post-Fire` - `Pre-Fire`,
    Metric = case_when(
      Metric == "Max_Temp"   ~ "Maximum Temp (°C)",
      Metric == "MWMT"       ~ "MWMT (°C)",
      Metric == "MWAT"       ~ "MWAT (°C)",
      Metric == "MWMT_DOY"   ~ "MWMT (Julian Day)",
      Metric == "Mean_Range" ~ "Mean Range",
      Metric == "Max_Range"  ~ "Max Range",
      Metric == "Days_18C"   ~ "Days > 18 °C",
      Metric == "Consec_18C" ~ "Consec. Days > 18 °C",
      TRUE ~ Metric 
    )
  ) %>%
  arrange(site, Metric)

# Formatted Output
metrics_table <- final_table_df %>%
  kable(digits = 1, caption = "Table 6: Temperature Regime Shift Analysis (Excluding 2020 Fire Year)", na.string = "-") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "condensed"), full_width = TRUE) %>%
  column_spec(4, color = "#d7191c") %>%
  column_spec(5, bold = TRUE, background = "#f9f9f9") %>%
  collapse_rows(columns = 1, valign = "top")

